Item Fit

Item fit statistics are commonly reported in validation studies with the Rasch model, as they indicate how well items describe the continuum of a latent trait. The item fit shows how accurately or predictably data fit the Rasch model. Several approaches to test if an item fits the scale exist, one commonly used statistic being the infit and outfit mean squares.

Infit and Outfit

Infit and outfit are mean-square residual summary statistics that range from zero to infinity. Good fit of an item can be expected when these statistics are close or equal to 1.

To find the item fit requires:

  1. to calculate the expected response for each observation \(X_{ij}\), i.e.the response for item \(i\) and person \(j\) based on the estimated person and item parameter.

\[E_{ij} = \Sigma^{mi}_{k=0} k (P_{ikj})\]

\(P_{ikj}\) is the probability of a person \(j\) responding \(k\) on item \(i\). The letter \(k\) stands for the response categories starting from 0, e.g.0 and 1 for a dichotomous data collection.

  1. to calculate a score residual \(Y_{ij}\):

\[Y_{ij} = X_{ij} - E_{ij}\] and a standardized residual \(Z_{ij}\):

\[Z_{ij} = \frac{Y_{ij}}{(W_{ij})^{1/2}}\]

where \(W_{ij} = \Sigma^{mi}_{k=0}(k-E_{ij})^2 P_{ikj}\) is the variance of \(X_{ij}\).

  1. The standardized residuals are squared and summed to form a Chi-square statistic:

\[\chi^2 = \Sigma^N_{n=1}Z_{ij}^2\]

  1. The chi-square statistic divided by N corresponds to the Mean-Square Outfit statistic

\[Outfit_i = \frac{\Sigma^N_{n=1}Z_{ij}^2}{N}\]

The outfit statistic is sensitive to outlier, i.e.off-target information.

  1. to diminish this effect of the Outfit statistic, the Mean-Square Infit adjusts the squared standardized residuals \(Z_{ij}^2\), by their individual variances, \(W_{ij}\):

\[Infit_{i} = \frac{\Sigma^N_{n=1}W_{ij}Z_{ij}^2}{\Sigma^N_{n=1}W_{ij}}\] The variance \(W_{ij}\) is found above, the same for standardizing the residuals.

# Example : outfit and infit equation in R for the dichotomous case
library(eRm)

# a simulated sample
data.test <- eRm::sim.rasch(500, 10, seed = 1234)

# running the Rasch model
RM.test <- RM(data.test)

# extracting the person.parameter these are required to extract residuals,
# probabilities, and fit statistics
PP <- person.parameter(RM.test)

# getting the residuals
Zij <- residuals(PP)

# residuals squared for the equation
Zij_square <- Zij^2

# Outfit
Outfit <- colSums(Zij_square)/nrow(Zij)  #diy outfit
Outfit2 <- itemfit(PP)$i.outfitMSQ  #outfit from package

# compare
cbind(Outfit, Outfit2)

#################################################################### 

# infit requires computing the variance Wij

# the response probabilities
Probs <- pmat(PP)
# Expected response
Eij <- Probs * 1 + (1 - Probs) * 0

# Variance
Wij <- (1 - Eij)^2 * Probs + (0 - Eij)^2 * (1 - Probs)

# Infit
Infit <- colSums(Wij * Zij_square)/colSums(Wij)  #diy infit
Infit2 <- itemfit(PP)$i.infitMSQ  #infit from package

# compare
cbind(Infit, Infit2)

Underfit and Overfit

Under the null hypothesis, the expected value of the Infit and Outfit statistic of a fitting item is equal to one. Values much greater than one (> 1.3 for example) indicate underdiscrimination while values below one (< 0.7 for example) overdiscrimination.

Underdiscriminating items do not allow to differentiate person on a cut-off, the information is blurred. The sample cannot be stratified or measured with underdiscriminating items.

Overdiscriminating items are too sharp and do not add any information about relative performances to the scale. Overdiscriminating items act like an on/off switch but not like a measuring device.

In general, underdiscriminating items are more a problem for a measurement scale than overdiscriminating items.

T-statistic and P-values can be derived for the infit and outfit statistics to determine how significantly an items fit statistic is departing from what would be expected. For more details see (Smith, Schumacker, and Bush 1998).

Numeric Output Analysis

To calculate the item fit with eRm requires the itemfit() function which uses the output of the person.parameter object.

# starting with the PCM analysis
PCM.srg <- PCM(data.srg)


# first apply the person.parameter from the PCM run previously
PP.srg <- person.parameter(PCM.srg)


# having a look at the expected response probabilities and the residuals is
# possible with: pmat(PP.srg) residuals(PP.srg)

# however the package has all the functions to compute the itemfit()
Fit <- itemfit(PP.srg)

The columns Outfit MSQ and Infit MSQ are those we are interested in. The way to interpret this output can vary. Is it a population survey or is the scale for clinical use? How much is at stake? For the moment, we will rely on the cut-off values proposed by (Wright et al. 1994) here https://www.rasch.org/rmt/rmt83b.htm.

For a high stake test the infit and outfit statistics should be between 0.8 and 1.2 if items are fitting the Rasch scale.

The output shows that 2 items are overdiscriminating with an infit MSQ values \(< 0.8\): SRG-7 I learned to how to reach out and help others and SRG-14 I learned to stand up for my personal rights. Only one item is underdiscriminating and really problematic. Item SRG-15 I learned that there are more people who care about me than I thought have outfit and infit values of 1.622 and 1.421 which is above 1.2, the chosen cut-off.

Visual Analysis

Item fit problems could be detected with the item-category characteristic (ICC) curve. In principle, the ICC is used to observe the probabilities for item responses across the ability continuum. The following ICC plots show the expected response probability curve for an item along the ability continuum. Dots illustrate the true position of the respondents (or respondents groups) along the continuum.

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 3, method = "score")

The option cinumber divides the score continuum into the specified number of sample subgroups with all subgroups having approximately the same number of observations.

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 3, method = "cut", cinumber = 9, title = "Item Characteristic Curve: Item 1")

This ICC plot above shows the mean observed scores per class interval (the dots), they are rather well aligned along the expected characteristic curve.

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 7, method = "score", title = "Item Characteristic Curve: Item 7")

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 7, method = "cut", cinumber = 9, title = "Item Characteristic Curve: Item 7")

These are two of the items that showed some overfit earlier. It can be noticed, that the increase in the observed scores (the dots) is somewhat steeper than the estimated ICC curve. That is commonly observed in presence of overfit.

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 15, method = "score", title = "Item Characteristic Curve: Item 15")

ICCplot(data.srg, itemnumber = 15, method = "cut", cinumber = 9, title = "Item Characteristic Curve: Item 15")

The item 15 was the only item which was underfitting. It can be noticed, that the increase in the observed scores (the dots) is not consistently following the estimated ICC curve and that the observed change in observed score is flatter than predicted.
